00:11:11,971 --> 00:11:15,429
Send you in his place? I called.
They don't want you back.

205
00:11:15,541 --> 00:11:20,171
<i>Oscar had served in Vietnam</i>
<i>as a croc spotter on a Swift boat.</i>

206
00:11:20,279 --> 00:11:22,509
Croc! No, Sorry. Wait. Log.

207
00:11:22,615 --> 00:11:24,583
Just a log.
No, wait. Sorry. Croc!

208
00:11:24,684 --> 00:11:28,984
<i>It was there that he met</i>
<i>a young U.S.O. Dancer named Lucille.</i>

209
00:11:29,088 --> 00:11:30,953
<i>I prefer an older man.</i>

210
00:11:31,057 --> 00:11:35,653
- <i>Hey, I'm free after the show.</i>
- <i>I said older, Bob, not dead.</i>

211
00:11:37,496 --> 00:11:40,624
I swore I'd never
say his name again, but...

212
00:11:40,733 --> 00:11:43,395
it's time to call you-know-who.

213
00:11:43,502 --> 00:11:47,632
<i>"You-know-who"was</i>
<i>an army sergeant named Bill Anderson.</i>

214
00:11:47,740 --> 00:11:52,473
<i>He and Lucille were an item</i>
<i>before she left him for Oscar.</i>

215
00:11:52,578 --> 00:11:57,379
<i>At the studio, Tobias began to</i>
<i>create buzz around the watercooler.</i>

216
00:11:57,483 --> 00:11:59,474
That Fünke is some kind of something.

217
00:11:59,585 --> 00:12:01,849
Boy, this Fünke is all anybody's
ever talking about.

218
00:12:01,954 --> 00:12:05,287
So sick and tired of hearing about
how brilliant that Fünke is.

219
00:12:05,391 --> 00:12:09,452
Overrated.
I'll just move- I'm sorry.

220
00:12:09,562 --> 00:12:12,087
Okay. We're okay. Okay.

221
00:12:12,198 --> 00:12:15,827
<i>Meanwhile, Maeby looked for</i>
<i>an empty office to call George Michael.</i>

222
00:12:15,935 --> 00:12:20,031
Where are you? I bought you a day.
I can't put this book report off forever.

223
00:12:20,139 --> 00:12:22,334
<i>Sorry, is this your office?</i>

224
00:12:22,441 --> 00:12:25,968
No. I'm just sitting behind someone else's
desk pretending these are my kids.

225
00:12:26,078 --> 00:12:29,104
<i>Can you getJude Law</i>
<i>in here for a meeting?</i>

226
00:12:29,215 --> 00:12:31,274
- Oh, I'm just a reader.
- A reader?

227
00:12:31,383 --> 00:12:35,012
- Yeah.
- I need a report by tomorrow.

228
00:12:35,121 --> 00:12:39,751
<i>Before gym-lunch...</i>
<i>with Jim... Carrey.</i>

229
00:12:39,859 --> 00:12:42,123
It's the <i>Grinch</i> guy.
You're too young.

230
00:12:46,065 --> 00:12:49,865
So get this.
Sitwell loved my ideas.

231
00:12:49,969 --> 00:12:52,938
Well, my ideas and I knew it.
That's great.

232
00:12:53,038 --> 00:12:55,836
- You know, Dad never complimented any of those.
- Here's the thing.

233
00:12:55,941 --> 00:12:59,809
- I need <i>more.</i>
- There were 34 proposals in there.

234
00:12:59,912 --> 00:13:02,642
You'd be amazed how fast they come out
when you read them all in a row.

235
00:13:02,748 --> 00:13:06,878
"Thirty-one, bamboo floor upgrades.
Cheaper, stronger." I can't read this word.

236
00:13:06,986 --> 00:13:09,921
"Thirty-two, wireless 'crapability."'
That one explains itself.

237
00:13:10,022 --> 00:13:12,320
- "Thirty-three"-
- Gob, that was six-months' worth of work.

238
00:13:12,424 --> 00:13:14,392
- You can't just blurt them all out at once.
- <i>Mr. Bluth.</i>

239
00:13:14,493 --> 00:13:17,724
- He's coming. I've got to go.
- You blew them away.

240
00:13:17,830 --> 00:13:21,630
Bought you something. Maybe
we can play catch sometime.

241
00:13:21,734 --> 00:13:25,033
<i>Gob's own father had only</i>
<i>once played catch with him.</i>

242
00:13:25,137 --> 00:13:29,233
<i>And it ended as badly</i>
<i>as any game of catch could end.</i>

243
00:13:29,341 --> 00:13:32,469
- White power!
- Better yet, maybe we can play ball on Saturday.

244
00:13:32,578 --> 00:13:35,547
I'll meet you there.
I've got a neck hair fitting at 11:00.

245
00:13:35,648 --> 00:13:40,608
<i>Gob was both angry...</i>
<i>and overwhelmed...</i>

246
00:13:40,719 --> 00:13:43,847
<i>by the approval</i>
<i>from this new father figure.</i>

247
00:13:43,956 --> 00:13:47,016
<i>It was confusing.</i>

248
00:13:47,126 --> 00:13:50,027
<i>Michael was less torn</i>
<i>and went to brag to his father.</i>

249
00:13:50,129 --> 00:13:54,862
So, apparently my ideas aren't so bad,
and that comes from Sitwell himself.

250
00:13:54,967 --> 00:13:58,698
- You let your ideas go to Sitwell?
- Uh, no. I gave them to Gob...

251
00:13:58,804 --> 00:14:02,535
who, uh, works there now.

252
00:14:02,641 --> 00:14:04,609
You let Gob go to Sitwell?

253
00:14:04,710 --> 00:14:07,008
- What'd I tell you? I told you-
- "Don't let him go." I know.

254
00:14:07,112 --> 00:14:10,047
- But my point is that I do all the work, Pop.
- He makes all the plays.

255
00:14:10,149 --> 00:14:12,481
Don't you understand? He was the best
softball player in the league.

256
00:14:12,585 --> 00:14:17,716
<i>Gob was especially gifted</i>
<i>at sacrificing his body for the play.</i>

257
00:14:17,823 --> 00:14:20,951
- <i>Play's at second. Play's at second.</i>
- Yeah! Suck on that, Sitwell.

258
00:14:21,060 --> 00:14:23,551
<i>Although at times,</i>
<i>even that wasn't enough.</i>

259
00:14:23,662 --> 00:14:26,495
Your Tweety Bird dance
just cost us a run, you moron.

260
00:14:26,599 --> 00:14:28,829
<i>Why do you think</i>
<i>Sitwell hired him?</i>

261
00:14:28,934 --> 00:14:32,301
You can't do this. You're gonna lose the game,
the company, and you can't do this.

262
00:14:32,404 --> 00:14:35,396
What are you saying? If I win the game,
you're comfortable with me running the company?

263
00:14:35,507 --> 00:14:37,634
- That's what I'm saying.
- I'll win the game.

264
00:14:37,776 --> 00:14:41,007
And I'll show him that
his little plan didn't work, all right?

265
00:14:41,113 --> 00:14:44,742
- We can build houses. We can win games.
- That is what I wanna hear.

266
00:14:44,850 --> 00:14:48,911
We can win games.

267
00:14:50,522 --> 00:14:54,424
Lindsay, did that oven vent hit you?
Your foot is bleeding.

268
00:14:54,526 --> 00:14:58,121
My foot is bleeding.
- <i>Teamocil may cause</i>
<i>numbness of the extremities.</i>

269
00:14:58,230 --> 00:15:00,198
You're gonna be able
to play on our team, right?

270
00:15:00,299 --> 00:15:03,598
- Why do you think I'm taking Teamocil?
- To curb your sex drive.

271
00:15:03,702 --> 00:15:05,602
That's right. What team
are you talking about?

272
00:15:05,704 --> 00:15:09,299
<i>It may also cause</i>
<i>short-term memory loss.</i>

273
00:15:09,408 --> 00:15:12,104
<i>Okay. Looks like I'm gonna need</i>
<i>that female backup player after all.</i>

274
00:15:12,211 --> 00:15:15,146
- And Ann's really good at softball, huh?
- <i>Yeah. She's amazing.</i>

275
00:15:15,247 --> 00:15:17,841
You know, she's got this low center
of gravity. You can't knock her over.

276
00:15:17,950 --> 00:15:20,680
- Well, <i>I</i> could knock her over.
- Dad, I'm telling you, you can't.

277
00:15:20,786 --> 00:15:23,016
<i>They call her "The Wall,"</i>
<i>you know?</i>

278
00:15:23,122 --> 00:15:27,286
Well, that's great. But I could
knock her over. I won't, but I could.

279
00:15:27,393 --> 00:15:30,021
- <i>And Lucille called on an old lover.</i>
- William?

280
00:15:30,129 --> 00:15:32,563
- Yes, ma'am?
- You don't remember me?

281
00:15:32,665 --> 00:15:36,795
<i>General Anderson had done</i>
<i>three tours of duty in Vietnam...</i>

282
00:15:36,902 --> 00:15:41,862
- <i>but the only memory he'd blocked</i>
<i>was being left by Lucille.</i>
- Oh, God. That touch.

283
00:15:41,974 --> 00:15:45,842
- Oh, how could I forget? Pat?
- Lucille.

284
00:15:45,945 --> 00:15:48,812
I could never forget that touch.

285
00:15:48,914 --> 00:15:52,645
Bill, they're shipping my son Buster off.
I can't have that happen.

286
00:15:52,751 --> 00:15:57,051
- I'm sorry. There's nothing I can do.
- Is there anything I can do?

287
00:15:58,357 --> 00:16:03,420
Maybe if you... go downtown.

288
00:16:03,529 --> 00:16:07,397
Oh, I haven't done that in 30 years.

289
00:16:17,876 --> 00:16:20,606
You make me want to puke, Bluth!

290
00:16:20,713 --> 00:16:23,511
<i>And so, Buster was pulled out</i>
<i>of combat training</i>-

291
00:16:23,615 --> 00:16:28,177
- Put 'em down and halt!
- <i>and put into U.S.O. Training.</i>

292
00:16:31,557 --> 00:16:35,516
- It jolts, but it's not really doing it right now.
<i>- And back at Gob's new office.</i>

293
00:16:35,627 --> 00:16:37,424
- Michael.
- Do you still need those ideas?

294
00:16:37,529 --> 00:16:40,362
<i>Come on. Are you kidding me?</i>
<i>I can't let Sitwell down.</i>

295
00:16:40,466 --> 00:16:44,027
- L-I'm desperate here.
- Then I'll make you a deal.

296
00:16:44,136 --> 00:16:48,129
- I want you to throw the softball game.
- Never!

297
00:16:48,240 --> 00:16:50,902
- He gave me this.
- Course he did. Why do you think he hired you?

298
00:16:51,010 --> 00:16:53,877
He liked my ideas.

299
00:16:53,979 --> 00:16:55,879
They were my ideas,
and, no, he didn't.

300
00:16:55,981 --> 00:16:59,712
He wants you for the softball game because
he's trying to make our family look foolish.

301
00:16:59,818 --> 00:17:04,653
I knew you had bad ideas.
All right, we'll play <i>him.</i>

302
00:17:04,757 --> 00:17:07,385
I'll throw that softball game.

303
00:17:07,493 --> 00:17:10,724
Nobody makes a fool of
our family without my help.

304
00:17:17,102 --> 00:17:21,334
<i>Tobias had talked up the name</i>
<i>Fünke, and it was time to audition.</i>

305
00:17:21,440 --> 00:17:24,170
- What's your name?
- Tobias.

306
00:17:24,276 --> 00:17:26,301
He's too short. Give it to the guard.

307
00:17:26,412 --> 00:17:31,748
Oh. L- I'm not. L-
On camera, I seem much taller.

308
00:17:31,850 --> 00:17:35,149
<i>And Maeby picked up the reader's report,</i>
<i>which had now become her book report.</i>

309
00:17:35,254 --> 00:17:37,950
- Whatcha got there?
- I can't really discuss it.

310
00:17:38,057 --> 00:17:40,457
If you wanna get it made,
I'm the guy who has to see it.

311
00:17:40,559 --> 00:17:44,188
You're the Fünke everyone's talking about?
What are you, like, 15?

312
00:17:44,296 --> 00:17:48,164
- Marry me.
- Everyone thinks I look young too.

313
00:17:48,267 --> 00:17:51,259
- So who are you thinking about?
- Jude Law. Why do you ask?

314
00:17:51,370 --> 00:17:53,838
Yeah. Go young<i>. Young Guy and the Sea.</i>
Big spring-breaker.

315
00:17:53,939 --> 00:17:56,931
Four C.G.I. The fish.
Let's fast-track this one.

316
00:17:57,042 --> 00:18:00,443
<i>And that's when Maeby realized</i>
<i>she had become a successful film executive.</i>

317
00:18:00,546 --> 00:18:02,707
- It's all waxed up.
- All waxed up? What do you mean?

318
00:18:02,815 --> 00:18:05,807
- I need something. Ajob for my dad.
- Yeah, yeah. Sure. Okay.

319
00:18:05,918 --> 00:18:09,285
Listen to me.
Brand new cars don't get waxed!

320
00:18:09,388 --> 00:18:11,856
<i>That afternoon it was game time...</i>

321
00:18:11,957 --> 00:18:14,448
<i>and Michael felt confident</i>
<i>about a Bluth win.</i>

322
00:18:16,962 --> 00:18:19,192
Spin, spin, spin.

323
00:18:19,298 --> 00:18:24,031
<i>Ann wasn't as amazing as</i>
<i>George Michael led his father to believe.</i>

324
00:18:25,104 --> 00:18:27,299
<i>But Gob was playing</i>
<i>worse than ever...</i>

325
00:18:27,406 --> 00:18:30,307
<i>as per his agreement with Michael.</i>

326
00:18:37,749 --> 00:18:41,082
<i>Your guy can't hit, Sitwell.</i>
<i>He's never gonna touch it.</i>

327
00:18:41,186 --> 00:18:43,245
- Time out.
- Time out.

328
00:18:43,355 --> 00:18:45,482
Gob, are you okay?

329
00:18:45,591 --> 00:18:48,389
Yeah, just can't hit today.
Guess you're really disappointed in me.

330
00:18:48,494 --> 00:18:51,657
Hey. Everybody has days like this.
It's only a game.

331
00:18:51,763 --> 00:18:54,823
After that list of ideas you gave me,
I don't care if you blow the whole season.

332
00:18:54,933 --> 00:18:57,663
Come here, you.

333
00:18:59,071 --> 00:19:00,834
Okay. We're good.

334
00:19:00,939 --> 00:19:04,898
<i>And Gob finally felt</i>
<i>that someone believed in him.</i>

335
00:19:05,010 --> 00:19:08,673
<i>Even though they weren't his ideas.</i>

336
00:19:08,780 --> 00:19:11,408
<i>And he decided</i>
<i>to make Sitwell proud.</i>

337
00:19:14,553 --> 00:19:16,680
<i>Get on that ball!</i>

338
00:19:19,024 --> 00:19:21,515
You go!

339
00:19:21,627 --> 00:19:23,527
You better pull an ankle or something.

340
00:19:23,629 --> 00:19:25,529
<i>Come on, George Michael!</i>
<i>Get that ball in there!</i>

341
00:19:25,631 --> 00:19:27,690
<i>Then he went headfirst into The Wall.</i>

342
00:19:27,799 --> 00:19:29,767
- I'm safe.
- You're out!

343
00:19:29,868 --> 00:19:33,201
<i>Out? I was safe! I'm safe!</i>

344
00:19:33,305 --> 00:19:36,365
- Stop with the Tweety Bird dance, you moron.
- Dad?

345
00:19:36,475 --> 00:19:38,807
He made the call. You're out.
What are you doing?

346
00:19:38,911 --> 00:19:40,708
- Shush, shush, shush.
- Dad?

347
00:19:40,812 --> 00:19:43,212
- He's safe.
- What the hell are you doing here?

348
00:19:43,315 --> 00:19:46,409
I'm taking care of what you
screwed up. You blew it again, Michael.

349
00:19:46,518 --> 00:19:50,887
Let me tell you something. I blew it when
I let you start controlling me again.

350
00:19:50,989 --> 00:19:52,889
I even stooped to cheat here
at a softball game.

351
00:19:52,991 --> 00:19:55,391
You've been talking to each other.
How come nobody called me?

352
00:19:55,494 --> 00:19:58,793
- What's going on there?
- I'm just fixing something that's been bugging me.

353
00:19:58,897 --> 00:20:01,491
<i>He was safe.</i>

354
00:20:01,600 --> 00:20:05,229
He was. We lost.
Get over it.

355
00:20:05,337 --> 00:20:08,829
Yeah, and Stan Sitwell liked my ideas.
He really believed in me.

356
00:20:08,941 --> 00:20:10,738
- My ideas.
- Well.

357
00:20:10,842 --> 00:20:13,743
And I'm president, whether
you like it or not, Dad.

358
00:20:13,845 --> 00:20:15,972
I don't need your approval anymore.

359
00:20:17,549 --> 00:20:20,848
- I'm proud of you.
- Really?

360
00:20:20,953 --> 00:20:23,046
Yeah. See ya.

361
00:20:26,058 --> 00:20:28,583
Michael, I could've sworn
I just saw Dad.

362
00:20:28,694 --> 00:20:32,095
Or not. I think hallucination
is one of the side-effects ofTeamocil.

363
00:20:32,197 --> 00:20:34,324
<i>It isn't.</i>

364
00:20:34,433 --> 00:20:36,731
- Thanks for making the right call there, Mike.
